Photo by National Park Geek® in Katmai National Park & Preserve with @chasedekkerphotography, @alaska.geographic, @katmaiconservancy, and @katmainpp. May be an image of nature.

node.text:
It’s nice to go on a family stroll in a park. 
•••••
Thanks to Chase  @chasedekkerphotography for the Katmai adventure. 
•
During my time with the coastal brown bears of the Alaskan Peninsula, my focus was not on their fishing habits, which many visitors head here to witness. Instead, I was in an area where they were mostly feeding on sedge grass and clams, which could be found only during low tide. I particularly enjoyed watching the bears dig for clams as it took a little more effort on their part to sniff, dig, and break the clams apart with their claws, compared to the constant head-down grass grazing. As the tide would recede, many bears would make their way up and over the grassy knolls and down across the exposed mud flats. Quite a few sows and cubs would wander across the mud for hours, or as long as the tide would allow them to, looking for as many meaty clams as possible. The young cubs were not quite ready to dig for their own, but all of them would watch their respective mothers closely to see how it was done. When the tides would begin to approach and rise, the bears knew it was time to move back into the meadows, leaving the bay back to the seals, sea otters, and Stellar sea lions that waited for the deeper water to return.

node.text:
The stories that have been told…. Find a #smallparksaturday like a visit to Sagamore Hill NHS. You will leave with some great stories. 

Sending thoughts of safety to all those in the path of this weekends east coast Hurricane. Be safe and stay dry. 
•••••
Thanks to our friends @friendsofsagamorehill Give them a follow and help them to tell the stories from Roosevelt’s beloved home. 
•
On a beautiful August night like this evening, one can’t help but to think of what some of those evenings at the Summer White House must’ve been like.  It is said that often after dark, Theodore Roosevelt used to join his Secret Service detail on the piazza at Sagamore Hill and exchange stories.  One can only imagine those musings! Exchanging old Rough Rider stories, and bygone adventures, of service to flag and country, as the old steamboat lights went up and down the Long Island Sound. 

What is especially fascinating is that TR was the very first President to be assigned Secret Service detail full time, after William McKinley was assassinated in 1901.  Before that, the Secret Service, which was founded in 1865, was mainly used to monitor the nations currency, because there was so much counterfeiting going on after the Civil War.  So, there would not have been many previous details exchanged on guarding Presidential homes.  The men were learning on the job at Sagamore Hill. 

Photo: Moonlit evening sky over Sagamore Hill 

Source(s): americanhistory.si.edu
@jgwa_architects
